data: Go on and pop him, Tom.
Christ, Tom, you can't feel sorry for these animals. A guy like this, would plug you if you give him the chance. You gotta pull the trigger without thinkin’.
No... no, no wait...please...I don’t wanna fuckin' die...
Ah Christ, Tom. Snap outta it. Remember what those guys wanted to do to Sarah?
Guess I’m out. But this one’s finished too.
Hey. Let’s get outta here before the bulls show up, huh?
My cousin in the prairies is all caught up in the Dust Bowl. You seen the latest pictures? Like living in hell.
Yeah. You do what you're told, and you kick up the money. Just have to wait till the guy above you shits the bed.
Good to see you. Thanks for coming.
Ha ha, good man. Have another for me.
As long as the bar stays open, Councilor.
Hey, John! Hope you’re enjoying yourself?
Tried to go sidelong into five brick walls. But we made it.
Don't know if this thing’s gonna make it back to the track, let alone get on the start line...
My mother, she would be so honored if you tried her caponata.
I’ve been looking forward to this all week. Wait’ll you taste the cassata, Tommy.
Ey! More wine here, please! Quickly!
You’re going to love this wine, it’s a-
Don Salieri! Welcome, my friend! Welcome!
Yes! Ey, come! Our guest has arrived!
No. I put her up to it.
And to drink, a chianti. I’ve been saving this just for you.
Molto bene. Oh, let me get you chair for you, ah? Sit, please.
Sarah threatened to leave me if I didn’t dry out.
I’m glad you’re off the roof, Tom.
Bastard could’ve at least let me finish my wine...
Molto grazie Don Salieri. Praise from such a gourmet as you, it fill me with joy.
Ah, you wouldn’t call me a gourmet if you knew what I had for supper ---
Ah ha ha, Pepé! The meal is a masterpiece, as always.
Drunkards get sloppy, Tom. I didn’t want you to make a mistake we couldn’t live with.
Hey Salieri! Come outta there, and we’ll make this quick!
Why's he pointin' a gun at him!
That’s true, but I’m sayin’ you gotta go home too before you resurface the pit lane.
Cow says “moo” and a chicken says “quack”, what does a bird say?
I don’t know but the security guy back there says you gotta go home.
Guy’s an asshole. He should show some respect!
Wait... That’s the guy! That’s the guy who killed Billy!
No matter how far we’ve fallen, we can find redemption in death. Now William, he was a sinner, yes, but he was also a loving son, a protective brother, and a loyal friend.
And now, I believe one of Billy’s closest and dearest friends would like to say a few words.
And for those virtues, we pray that his soul finds salvation.
I uh... I just wanted to pay my respects...
I can’t even count all the times you saved my ass from a beatin’. Don’t know how I could --
Billy, I never said this, but I considered you my brother.
We’re going to ambush these boys. I’ll keep them entertained while you slip out the back and circle around.
We aren’t going out the front door... Can you move?
Blow them all down, Tommy. Not one of them goes home tonight.
I gotta get you to a doctor...
That can wait! Get Sam outta there!
Tell Salieri from here on out this place is ours. Capisce? And don't come back, or you'll end up in worse shape than your friends.
Get Sam. They’re tryin’ to beat information out of him...
Paulie, move that car so I can get the truck down and out of here. Little Bill, stick with Gates till we know the place is clear.
I hate it out here. Like when we sit in a field doing some booze handover or something. It’s always knee-deep in shit, and most times it’s dark and cold as hell.
Tommy, what are you doing? Take ‘em out!
He was hidin’ out in Europe. But the dumb bastard started bettin’ at the dog track. He got spotted by a friend of the family. So, Salieri... sent out a crew...
Nobody’s carrying you to the doctor this time, Sam.
You kill me now, and the Don? He’s never gonna stop lookin’ for you... But you let me live... I’ll tell Salieri you’re dead. You can disappear, just like Frank.
Only you’ll be smart enough to stay gone, right?

You can’t do it, can you? Always that little voice in the back of your head... Maybe sounds like your baby girl or Sarah... Always tellin’ you not to pull that trigger... And you can’t make up your mind...
It’s gettin’ easier every time you open your fuckin’ mouth.
Hah... We sure had some laughs, right? Remember that time me, you, and Paulie --
No one ever sees the hairpin until it’s too late. But, you didn’t get handed a heater in the nursery, did you?
No. I was a cab driver. Back in ‘30...
No self-respectin’ badge is comin’ in here. Unless it’s the health inspector.
But I got plenty to trade.
Can’t even pay for the coffee.
Well if you’re looking to set up a gravy train, you called the wrong cop. I’m not lookin’ for any... “associates.”
So, you said on the phone you might have a proposition for me?
Three years. Cut my teeth in Empire Bay.
How long you been in town?
An’ no one else to watch your back, I’m guessin’.
Tough break. Case must be gettin’ pretty cold by now...
What, you got somethin’ might warm it up?
An’ they handed you the Morello case, right outta the gate?
That’s what the paper says, ain’t it? And what’s it to you?
None of that. I got people I need to protect.
Ah. Family’s always the Achilles heel, ain’t it? So, who you got? A sick ma? Or a wife and a litter of kids?
And what’s my end of the deal? You want money? Some sort of immunity?
Christ. I don’t know how everything got so balled up...
Either way looks like I’m buyin’ you a cup of coffee.
You think I’m on the run?
Look, I can’t promise anything for your family. Not until I hear what you’re tradin’. So, are you talkin’ or are you just killin’ time before they come for you?
But, you stick around, tell me your story, and maybe you got a shot at livin’ long enough to walk that girl of yours down the aisle.
Pity that. Pa always said a man needs friends if he’s going to survive in this world.
Yeah, well, in my world it’s the other way around.
You can let me off here.
The Don tried to drown her. I broke his nose.

Good, because you need to think about your career here. Look, Paulie’s hit his ceiling. He’s the guy we want in a tussle, but he’s not smart enough to run anything. Sam is loyal, but, he has no vision. But you, Tommy,
you could run this town someday.
No. Pregnant. She went into heat, got out of the yard, and every dog in town had a turn.
You’re like that dog, Tommy. Every time you flash your money around, you’re a bitch in heat, and everyone in that club is now looking to fuck you. And once you get fucked, you’re no good to us.
So, what happened to the dog?
Sure. Little mutt, when I was a kid.
You ever have a dog, Tom?
I don’t care about the bar fight, Tom. I care how it looks when you walk into a club and buy everyone a round.
Yeah, we got into a little scrap last night, it’s no big deal.
Then blow it at the track on Sunday. Or take a dame to a show. Or invest it, for Christ’s sake.
Ah, we gotta do something with our dough.
Don’t sass me, Tommy. I’m trying to teach you the ropes so you don’t get strangled by them.
You want me to become one of those Wall Street boys?

I know it’s a snipe hunt. Every little mobster goes to bed dreaming about that last big score. But if we do this thing, I don’t know, it might be just enough to get me a little pizzeria or something. You know?
So, you’re looking for the big one now?
You ain’t built for the domestic life, Paulie. Six months in, you’ll put a bullet in your brain outta boredom.

Yeah, I don’t know what it’s like for you, goin’ home to your wife and kid. But that’s why I’m doin’ this. Who’s gonna marry me, nearly forty years old and nothin’ to show for it but my rap sheet? But, we do this, I get enough scratch to finally get out. Who knows?
Watch it, buddy. You’re treading into enemy territory without a map.
You got a family to look after, I get that. But think about what this could mean for them.
Sure. But, if we’re doing this, we’re waiting until things calm down.
Why do you think you’re here? Vinny’s got it all figured out.
The councilor is celebrating his birthday with a big shindig on a steamboat. He’s pulling out all the stops. Booze, broads, fireworks. He’s even giving a speech to the press.

Soon. But first, we have to soften him up. Morello's got the cops, the politicians, and even some judges in his pocket. We can’t afford to buy them all off, so we need to scare them into abandoning Morello’s sinking ship.
We bump off the right idiot, the rest are going to realize sticking with Morello ain’t too good for their health.
First in line for the pine box is this asshole. Ghillotti. The Councilor is still seeing red over his dead kid, so he’s never going to turn on Morello.
Christ, that guy’s been giving us fits since ‘32. Let me take care of him, boss.
Sam and Paulie are down the docks working on that. You meet up with them there, and they’ll fill you in on the rest of the details.
Sure. But you got a plan for getting back to shore?
We want it done in public, to get people talking.

And then you just cool your heels. Mingle. Try not to look like a hatchet man until Ghillotti makes his appearance. You wait for that bastard to start his speech, and only then do you put one between his eyes.

Don’t go gettin’ creative on me. You’re still gonna shoot him, for fuck’s sake... When you get on deck, you make for the head. We got a janitor on the take, and he’s planted a revolver in the bathroom.
So, what, throw him overboard, see if he can swim?
Slow down, junior. Ghillotti is corrupt, but he ain’t stupid. His crew will be searchin’ everyone who comes on board, so you can’t be carryin’.
Okay. I’ll talk my way into the party and put two in his head.
Just his normal detail, a few guys with roscoes. None of the other fellas are gonna do dick to protect that piece of shit.
Okay, Ghillotti’s done, boss. You won’t have to worry about him after tonight.
Tom. Just be quick about it.

Morello was always windin’ us up, but he never did anything that might start an all-out war. Learnin’ Salieri was building his own bench must’ve finally tipped his scales. Because in ‘35, he hit us with both barrels...
Christ... That was the missin’ piece...

Well, a few years back, the vice squad got a judge on solicitation of a minor. Once in the box, he started confessing to all sorts of misbehavin’, tryin’ to get a deal. But he copped to takin’ kickbacks from Morello and your man Salieri. Playin’ ‘em off one another tryin’ to goose the take, but, once Morello found out, he threatened to bury the judge’s kids on the beach, still breathin’ of course...
Huh. That’s interestin’... You think Salieri was sourcin’ highbinders in ‘34?
Yeah, that was it. And Salieri, he finally starts talkin’ about gettin’ outta Morello’s shadow. Maybe buyin’ our own cops, our own politicians.
Workin’ up to it, maybe. But then, Prohibition ended and the bootleggin’ business got knocked on its ass. All that fightin’ over booze meant next to nothin’...
Sounds like Salieri was gettin’ ready to make his move?
We did it, we did it!
Way I hear it, Joey was just drivin’ to the gym one mornin’...
Probably daydreamin’ about winnin’ the belt or somethin’.
Moron! You drivin’ with your goddamn eyes closed? Look at this!
Oh, Jesus, Mary and Joseph... Don... Don Morello. I didn’t know it was you.
You know anybody else driving a rare import in this part of town, Joey?
No. And I’m sorry. I was drivin’ real slow...
You saying this is my fault?
You’re not gonna need that, sir. Tires are just fine. The grills a little bent up, is all. I got a cousin that can --
Well, repairs are gonna be expensive.
I just...I just, I ain’t--I ain’t never been in no accident...
Two lunch specials, please. And more coffee. You know what? Just bring the whole pot.
Alright, we’ve come this far together. What kinda heat did you get from the church?
Maybe, if you think you could make any of it stick. But, then you’d never know about Morello.
Hey fellas, sorry to keep you waitin’, my shift just started. What you havin’?
And I ain’t even to the hard stuff yet.
You know I could take you in right now and put you behind bars until you’re old and gray.
Jesus Christ, Tommy, you’re confessin’ to a shootout in a church.

Bastard knew we were bleedin’ out before we did... While we were busy keeping our heads down, he started movin’ in on our rackets. Quiet at first. A few trucks go missin’. A top earner has one too many highballs, drives off a bridge. One of our regular pick ups suddenly closes up shop, moves upstate.
And every time I went into Salieri’s, there was Sarah. So, it was a good year. Until Frank...
Yeah. That’s right. He set me straight. He set us all straight...
Ah, c’mon, I’m kidding. Hey, I couldn’t have done this without you, I know that. Go home, celebrate with Sarah. Come by my place in the mornin’, we’ll split the dough.
We did it! I can’t believe we fuckin’ did it! We’re loaded! We’re loaded!
When you catch up to Frank, you get those books. And if he doesn’t have ‘em on him, you make him tell you where to find them. After that... You do what we gotta do.
More than fifty years, I’ve known him. Everything I have, I got with Frank.

I was up all night, driving myself nuts trying to figure it out. I started thinking, maybe it’s one of our guys we aren’t paying his fair share. Someone with a light wallet, maybe looking to Morello for a new suit. Frank wasn’t around, so I went to the safe to get the account books, to see who’s getting cents on the dollar he’s earned.
Hey boss. I came as soon as I got your message.
Frank respects one person in this whole town, and that’s you. This has gotta be some kind of misunderstanding.
And every buck we’ve earned, every dime we’ve paid out, it’s all logged in those books. Frank hands those over to the Feds, we’re finished.
I been calling him all day. I went by his place. He’s gone. His wife and kid are gone.
The one you tried to drown.
I don’t know. I’m sure he has his reasons. Maybe he’s still smarting over the dog...
I was a stupid kid, Tommy.
Yeah. Same one I shot, after he wouldn’t let me sink her.
Shake down all our stoolies. See who knows what.
But grudge or no grudge, we gotta get those books back.
We ain’t frails. We know who you work for.
Salieri might’ve been the big six when he was younger, but he’s all washed up now. It’s only a matter of time before Morello punches his ticket.
We going to have trouble here?
Trouble started back when you tried to steal our girl, chief.
You saps aren’t careful, you’ll end up in wooden overcoats.
Oh! Hey there, darlin’. You steppin’ out on us?
Ah, Hahaha, don’t cast a kitten, dollface. We’ll let your boyfriend watch, whaddaya say?
Then let’s see what you got, cake-eater.
I don’t need Salieri or anyone else. Not for this.
I’m proud of all of you.
Good work, son. I’m proud of you.
What about the kid from Kentucky?
Yeah, boss. We took care of it.
Looks like a thirty-eight. Morello’s boys caught up with you?
Excellent. I’ll work out the details with papa Gates. But once we’re running this Kentucky brown, we’ll be back in brass buttons.
Well, let’s see if this hooch was worth all the trouble.
Gettin’ shot will give Gates and his pop another reason to ice Morello outta the whiskey business.
Well, he took a slug to the shoulder. But, he’s a tough blocker. He and his crew dusted out as soon as we bumped off Morello’s hatchet men.
Okay, I’ll stay with Sam. You can take the truck back, call it a night.
Sam, Sam! We made it. We're at the doctor’s house.
Okay, we're here! Tom, you get Sam out. I'm gonna go wake up the doc.
Paulie? What the hell are you doing here so late?
Hey, ah... Evenin’, doc. I'm sorry to wake you, but um... We had a little accident. We got an injured man out here.
Go’on Tom. I’m gonna be fine.
The doc’s already got his hands full. No sense in both of us breathing down his neck.
Hey Tom. I just want to thank you for stepping in like you did. I had six months' rent ridin’ on that race. I’d be homeless now, if not for you.
I just did what the Don asked, Lucas.
Well, you gotta let me find a way to repay you. Stop by my garage when you get a chance. I might have a line on somethin’ that’ll turn a buck for you.
I knew you wouldn’t let us down, Tom!
You made us all a lot of money today. And Morello is gonna be pickin’ up pennies off the sidewalk for weeks!
Hah, he’s probably wearing cement boots by now, the poor bastard.
You’ve got a girl, right? I don’t want you blowing all that on booze and whores.
Here. You’ve earned every dollar of this. Take your girl out somewhere nice.
Good boy. Go get yourself a drink.
Nah. But, maybe I'll buy my ma a new coat.
That race was really somethin’, huh?
Well, I had my money on the other guy, so the drinks are on you.
I just got lucky, is all.
And hey, when you’re done celebratin’, you might want to find your buddy Paulie. He’s so drunk, he’s gonna get hit by a parked car.
Yeah, okay. I’ll get him home safe.
There. Now you’re ready for the pictures.
They just want to keep the machines running, till the white guys are hungry enough to come back to work.
Remember that money, jobs, even best pals will come and go. But family? Family is forever.
A long time ago, in another life, someone once told me that family is a man’s Achilles heel...
I’ve turned my back on people I thought were my friends...
I’ve kept a lot of hard promises...
Because everything I’ve done, both good and bad...
I’ve spent eight years totally alone...
Trying to find myself. So I could come home...

Now that I’m a lot older and just a bit wiser, I see that family is our greatest weakness. But it’s also our greatest strength. It gets us out of bed in the morning; it lets us chase our dreams, even when they’re moving too fast to catch; and it keeps us from falling over when we’re too tired to take another step.
So that’s how a regular palooka goes from cabbie to mob enforcer over night, is it? Just dumb luck?

It didn’t feel that way at the time... Me parkin’ on that particular street, takin’ a break just when Paulie and Sam are comin’ around the corner? What are the odds? It felt like... I don’t know, like someone was watchin’ out for us.

Whatever helps you sleep at night, pal. But it’s a lucky break, all the same. I mean, one day, you’re bustin’ your back doin’ an honest day’s work, in a city that’s been tryin’ to scrape you off its heel since the day you stepped off of the boat. And the next, you’re stuffin’ your pockets full of Salieri’s dirty money, and lordin’ it over the rest of us.

Yeah, it wasn’t like that. Back then, Salieri didn’t have the run of the city. For every buck Salieri made, Don Morello would turn ten. He paid off cops, politicians, judges. And anyone he couldn’t buy, he scared into lookin’ the other way.
He did seem to have this city jumpin’ at its own shadow, I’ll give you that.
You hear anything about Joey Crackers?
Got his name in the Morello file, sure. A boxer, right?
How ‘bout this one, Puh-Puh-Paulie. It-it ain’t huh-hot-ruh-rod, but it-it’ll get you across tuh-tuh-town.
An’ don’t let me catch you loafin’ off again!
One day I’m gonna cut your brake line, asshole...
Like I said, Ralphie here’s a cracked egg. But you bring him a stolen car, he’ll make it yours. Tom and me, we got a job to do, we need some wheels.
I’m sorry Ralphie, I’m just bustin’ your balls.
The f-fuh-fuck there, Paulie! Y-y-you can’t just sneak up on a guh-guh-guy like that!
Hey Genius! Haha! Get your head outta your ass!
We ain’t nothin’ alike, you got that, Ralph?
I suh-suh-see you’re still limping. Guess we got t-t-two cripples working here.

No. You two are off this job. You’re broken mirrors on this one... We’ll let the guy who killed Ghillotti take a crack. Tommy here has all the politicians scared. Maybe he can put Sergio in the ground.
What do I need to know about this guy?
Besides he’s got a lucky rabbit’s foot up his ass?
I guess it could've been worse, huh? We could be peelin’ you off the front of the train.
He just got a good break, is all.
Sergio Morello’s always been lucky. He was born with more brains than his brother, that’s for sure.

Sergio is Morello’s top earner. He controls the unions, which means he controls the docks and can tax everything that’s imported into the city. We kill him, and a big part of Morello’s income will be wiped out.
Any ideas on how to get to him? I don’t want to end up in a tree like these two.
I’ll take care of it, boss.
Get it done, Tommy. For all of our guys Morello’s killed, and all the money he’s taken out of our pockets.
Just don’t drop it. Or shake it. Or smoke near it. Yeah, it’s safe. Boom! Woo!
It’s a custom job. Attach it to the starter under his car, and he’ll be a human torch as soon as he turns the key.
You can ride in the back.
Uh. This is all we got, pal. ‘Sides, there’s only room for two in the cab.
Bet you say that to all the girls.
Forget about it. I know when to keep my head down.
Be sure to keep your head down, or this whole thing is blown.
Christ, Frank... Why didn’t you ask us for help?
Now you’ve been paid twice. You take the ladies wherever they wanna go.

I guess I just wanted out, one way or the other. I’m tired, Tommy. Tired of lying to my wife. Tired of checking under my car every time I take a Sunday drive. And tired of waiting for the Don to put two in my temple.
Get on the plane, March. For Alice. For me. Get on the god damn plane, please.
Not right now, honey. Just get buckled in. Tommy and I, we have some serious business to discuss.
Tell them to get on the plane.
Go on March, Alice. Get aboard.
It’s a key to a box in the Grand Imperial Bank downtown. I told Morello I’d hand it over after the plane was fueled and ready to go. His men were meant to fetch it before we left.
I figured as much. I’m sorry it had to be you, Tommy.
I wish it could have shaken out better, but Morello finally came after me.
Anything you want me to tell him?
Morello offered me a simple trade. The Don’s account books for our lives. And tickets out of this town.
It’s okay. You can come out.
I’m not so stupid, Tom. They’re safe. Morello was waiting for this.
You hand the books over yet?
My pedal is to the metal!
Yeah. I’m sober as a priest.
Tom, you take the car. Find a customs truck and meet us near the impound. Me and Paulie, we’ll go get the rest of the gear.
Ah, quit bustin’ my balls. I’m good.
I just get to day dreamin’, you know.

Yeah I fucking know. You do what you want, I won’t say nothin’. I owe you that much. But Salieri, he finds out you’re goin’ behind his back, you’ll be planted right next to Morello. You ask me, there ain’t no haul worth that.
He’s right, Paulie. Bring it to the Don, or let it go.
Nah. Not really. We can cut him in after we make the score. He’ll be bent, sure, but he won’t stay mad once he gets his share.
Well then we don’t tell him.
You want to step out on the Don?
We’re robbin’ the fucking Feds, ain’t we? What’s the difference?
Salieri is the goddamn difference, you nitwit. The Don sent us to steal these cigars. But ain’t no way he sanctions a bank job.
Would you relax? You’re making me nervous, playing around with your piece like that.
That so? I’d have figured there weren't enough room up there.
Sorry. Just got a lot on my mind, is all.
Yeah? Spill it, then. What’re you workin’ on?
Go ahead and laugh, assholes. You guys and the Don, none of you think I got plans. But you’re wrong. I got big plans.
Been thinkin’ about hitting up a savings and loan downtown.
Robbin’ a bank, that’s a little outta our league.
Sure. I been casin’ the place for months. I got it all worked out. I just need a few guys I can count on to watch my back.
I’m sure it’s more than enough.
Good. Don Salieri wants you to know that he is very grateful. So, if you ever need anything, maybe a loan or some honest work, don’t hesitate to ask. The Don doesn’t forget his friends.
Pull over in front of that bar.
You want a little something from the Don or not?
Compensation for your services and any damage to your car. This makes us square.
I wasn’t interested. The money was good, sure, but I didn’t want to get in with criminals. Better to be poor and alive than rich and dead. So right there, back then: I was out.
When I opened the envelope, I could've had a heart attack. Enough to fix the cab. Nearly enough to buy a new one. I thought about what Sam had said about work
One more thing. This matter stays between us. Anyone asks where you got that money, you won it at poker. And the scratches on your car? You swerved to keep from hitting a little old lady. You got it?
And already soldiers in Peponne’s mob. So what happened? How did they go from being best mates to Morello on the slab?
I don’t know... I didn’t even know they were friends.
What you don’t know could fill up the fuckin’ Chrysler building...
Yeah, I heard the story. So what?
After Morello, Salieri was beamin’, thinkin’ we ran the whole damn town. Me, I was just happy the war was over.
You dry your tears with a wad of hundreds, do you?
You don’t want the guy who was punchin’ tickets. You want the guy who was handin’ them out.
You’ll do life for this, Tom. Or maybe even the chair.
You fucking phantom... I’ve been chasin’ you for three god damn years.
Look again. The old man, that’s Don Peponne. The two younger guys are Morello and Salieri.
The Don’s books, the ones Frank stole... I have ‘em. They’re enough to put Salieri away forever, and they’re yours. Assuming we have a deal. My family for the Don.
So that’s what all this has been about, huh? You’re offerin’ up Salieri...
April. Morello’s wedding. Salieri was the best man.
Yeah, okay, I see it. That must be, what, 1920?

The thing is, you don’t see it when you’re out on the street scrapping, fighting for your life. Then, the guy next to you isn’t just your partner, he’s your brother. You’d stick a knife in someone for your brother, right? But at night, you lie awake wondering what he and the Don were whisperin’ about behind the bar.
I wasn’t about to give up the good life, I know that. I just told myself I was smarter than Morello. That I wouldn’t turn around one day and find Paulie or Sam pointin’ a gun at my head.
Wonderin’ if your best friend is hungry enough to betray you.
Get over here! I got him pinned down!
Sorry, pal. Guess we’re doin’ this the hard way.
We don’t have time for this.
Not you, ladies. Stay where we can see your pretty faces.
Good. Let’s get ‘em loaded and get outta here.
You sure we’re getting what we came for?
You’re a better wheelman anyway. Just don’t drive us into the bay.
I’m not riding in the back again.
Go see Ralphie about a car.

Don’t lay hands on anyone unless there is no other choice. Our clients need to understand that we provide a valuable service. They need to look at you and see Saint Michael. They need to believe you’ll protect them.
So let Morello stoop to breaking legs. We’re better than that. But, the bill’s still due and everyone pays up.
Bill at the motel was a little short last month. So, make sure he pays us the interest he owes.
So, Tommy, you’ll drive. Paulie and Sam can handle the rest. It’ll be routine.
Just a handful of stops today.
One day all the cops in this city will be on our dime...
Y-y-you know how t-t-to get into one of these T-Tommy?
A-and an afternoon to f-f-fix the window back up...
Elbow goes through. Reach inside. Easy.
Find a way in Tom. I’ll stick with the truck.
